body:
@petrochenkov 

> In MinGW ld.gold is in $PATH, but it can't produce Windows executables AFAIK. Won't this patch break everything on Windows by default?

I wouldn't be too worried about this, personally. That seems super unlikely to ever happen (if it doesn't support windows) and even if it does exist it'll exist as `ld.gold.exe` most likely which this isn't even probing for. @nagisa's point about OSes like FreeBSD and such also lean me towards just not checking the OS at all and blindly assuming that if `ld.gold` exists it's the "right linker" to use.

@brson I still think something like `-C linker="gcc -fuse-ld=gold"` is better to be claimed to be the default option, which can be overridden in common and well understood ways (i.e. by specifying  `-C linker="gcc -fuse-ld=something-different"`). In fact, the `gcc -fuse-ld=gold` is pretty much the standard way to enable gold linker at the moment, so it also would be familiar to those of us who are already using different linkers.

Sure, this would probably would need rustc to be smart-er about what’s already specified in `-C linker`, but surely that’s less of an issue than getting through an RFC process or figuring out what to do with the argument later. 

Also the change would be less intrusive, because we could just add relevant flags to [`TargetOptions::linker`](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/blob/master/src/librustc_back/target/mod.rs#L98) in all relevant target files instead of relying on these wonky cfgs somewhere deep inside compiler itself.
